The Independent Police Investigative Directorate (Ipid) has opened an investigation into the case of a man who was shot to death allegedly by a Tshwane metro police for failing to stop at a roadblock in Pretoria.Police have arrested a 27-year-old Tshwane metro police officer for allegedly shooting deadm the man in his car in Pretoria on Friday morning.It is believed the victim, Tsakani Rikhotso Shimange, was shot once in the chest through the front windscreen of his Toyota sedan. Some said the 38 year old bumped his vehicle into a metro police car, but the claim is yet to be verified.Shimange s relatives said his death came as a shock as he was not an aggressive person. He worked for the Department of Telecommunications and Postal Services.Netcare911 paramedics initiated CPR but the man died.According to the SAPS the Tshwane metro police officers stopped a metered taxi and the taxi driver tried to knock over one of the officers. Tshwane metro police officers were stopping vehicles in Hatfield, Tshwane, at approximately 9.30am. It is alleged that the Tshwane metro police officers stopped the meter taxi and the taxi driver tried to knock over the officer, the statement said.Athlenda Mathe Netcare911 spokesperson said when paramedics arrived on the scene, the man was found slumped in the driver s seat unresponsive. Netcare911 had three advanced life support paramedics on the scene and began initiating CPR, this went on for some time, Mathe said.The man is believed to be in his 30s and was declared dead on the scene.TMPD spokesperson Isaac Mahamba said the officer was being kept in custody at a local police station.Mahamba said the TMPD s internal affairs unit would also investigate the matter. They will also cooperate fully with the SAPS on the investigation. We appeal to the members of the public who might have witnessed the incident to contact SAPS or TMPD, Mahamba said.It has been claimed the victim had bumped his vehicle into a metro police car, which led to the shooting, but this has not been confirmed by authorities.In December, a traffic officer accused of killing a motorist claimed that he acted in self-defence.Sydney Nkabinde 49 who is attached to the Ekurhuleni metro police department told the South Gauteng High Court sitting in Randburg that he returned fire after Vuyo Xakane had opened fire at him.The incident took place on January 6, 2015 in Alberton on the East Rand.Nkabinde said Xakane fired three shots at him after he (Nkabinde) had alighted from his marked metro police vehicle.NONDUMISO ZWANEnondumisoz@thenewage.co.za